## Frequently Asked Questions

**What is sales order automation software?**

Sales order automation software receives incoming purchase orders from customers — by email, EDI, portal, or PDF — and converts them into structured ERP-ready sales orders without manual data entry. For distribution businesses, the key capability is handling unstructured formats: free-text emails, informal product descriptions, and orders that don't conform to a template. AI-native tools do this by interpreting meaning; legacy tools do it by matching patterns against pre-built templates.

**How much does sales order automation software cost?**

Costs vary significantly by approach. Template-based platforms like Conexiom typically run $30,000 to $60,000 per year for mid-market distributors, with additional costs for template creation and maintenance. Rossum starts at $18,000 per year for basic document processing. Esker is part of an enterprise AP suite priced at $50,000 or more annually. AI-native tools like OrderFlow are typically priced per order volume. The total cost of ownership over three years is often lower with AI-native systems because there's no per-customer template work and no IT dependency for format changes.

**Which sales order automation software integrates with SAP, Dynamics, or Sage?**

OrderFlow integrates with SAP, Microsoft Dynamics 365, Sage, and other major distribution ERPs via API. Conexiom and Esker also support SAP and Dynamics integrations, with Esker having broader enterprise ERP coverage. Rossum connects to most ERPs but requires custom integration work for some configurations. The more important question is whether the integration covers your specific ERP configuration, not just the platform name. A pilot that connects to your actual ERP instance is the reliable way to confirm compatibility before committing.

**How long does it take to implement sales order automation software?**

OrderFlow is typically operational in two to six weeks from kickoff to live processing. No per-customer template configuration is required, which removes the main source of delay. Conexiom's typical timeline is three to six months, including template creation for each customer format. Esker implementations typically run four to eight months within a larger AP suite deployment. Rossum requires custom model training for each document type, adding several weeks. For distributors who've been through a long implementation project before, the deployment timeline is a genuine differentiator.

**What is the difference between EDI and AI-based sales order automation?**

EDI requires both trading partners to conform to a shared data standard. It works well for large enterprise accounts who have invested in EDI infrastructure, but excludes most small and mid-size customers who won't or can't adopt it. AI-based sales order automation handles what customers already send — free-text emails, PDFs, spreadsheets, informal messages — without requiring any format change from the customer. For most distributors, EDI covers 30 to 40% of order volume and AI-based automation covers the remaining 60 to 70%. The two approaches are complementary, not competing.
